    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2459350015" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2459350015" />
    <a title="Edward" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1659159-edward"><img alt="Edward" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1308570322p2/1659159.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2459350015?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edward" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edward" href="/user/show/1659159-edward">Edward</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780252068942" href="/book/show/144920.Mist">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2459350015" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11668556343436795713">What can you say about a book where the author decides to kill off his main character, but is met with a derisive comment that the victim will have the last laugh? Fictional characters, he says, once created, can&apos;t be discarded. They live on but their authors do in fact die, and their creations achieve immortality, or as close to it as anyone can come in life on earth. <br/>	<br/>You can hear the objection - fiction is not real life, just a imaginary, a make-believe one. That raises further questions abou</span>
  <span id="freeText11668556343436795713" style="display:none">What can you say about a book where the author decides to kill off his main character, but is met with a derisive comment that the victim will have the last laugh? Fictional characters, he says, once created, can't be discarded. They live on but their authors do in fact die, and their creations achieve immortality, or as close to it as anyone can come in life on earth. <br />	<br />You can hear the objection - fiction is not real life, just a imaginary, a make-believe one. That raises further questions about what is "real". Great joys and great pains, those events that make life meaningful "come wrapped in an immense MIST of trifling incidents. Life is just this - mist [often translated "fog"] Life is a nebula and out of it arises . . ." <br />	<br />Most of the time, though, "nearly all of us are boring ourselves unconsciously. Tedium is the foundation of life and it is tedium that invented all the games and distractions, the novels, and love." As if it were a wine press, "tedium" , squeezes from life a bitter-sweet liquor, any kind of creative endeavor, which in this novel turns out to be love. <br />	<br />What is depicted in this novel are the daily events of one Augusto who emerges from his personal "nebula" and falls in love with Eugenia. The "great joy" of his life is love, but it is indeed a bitter-sweet experience. Euigenia scorns him, thinking him a nincompoop, which he generally is. He reacts to Eugenia's rejection by finding another woman, but in the end returns to Eugenia who by now decided he is is not so bad after all. More surprises thwart a happy love ending., Augusto confides, discouraged, in his only true confident, Orpheo, his dog.<br />	<br />He wonders "how you can tell that a man is really in love and does not merely think it to be so?" Love's illusions are many, and a dog can't give answers. Here is where the author comes in; Augusto decides to talk over his dilemma with Unamuno who after all wrote the novel. Augusto, now despairing, , decides to commit suicide, but the author says he'll spare him the trouble and simply kill him off. At which point, Augusto shifts direction again and decides that he wants to live, after all, and in fact will live. He exists and the author, at this stage, simply can't remove him from existence. <br />	<br />It's finally unclear whether he killed himself or was technically "killed" by the author. All that's known is that the servant finds his lifeless body, and thinks she is going mad when Augusto speaks and tells her he can't be killed. A Dracula finale? Almost, with more talk that without the word, nothing exists (reminiscent of the beginning of John's gospel, "in the beginning was the word. . .").<br />	<br />An epilogue concludes this drolly surreal book with Augusto's faithful dog, Orfeo, having the last word, expressing that in a pure platonic world of ideas lives the idea of pure dog alongside his flawed master. You might consider this a philosophical book interrupted by the fog of daily life which has rolled in.. Or if you find all of this tedious, it could be a book of daily life, potentially a satisfying love story, which has been obscured by a dense fog of aesthetic and philosophical questions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11668556343436795713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


