<div id="review_2973857430" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2973857430" />
    <a title="Kelly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1380226-kelly"><img alt="Kelly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1575382684p2/1380226.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2973857430?book_show_action=true">Sep 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly" href="/user/show/1380226-kelly">Kelly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780810135369" href="/book/show/32072611-fog">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2973857430" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17318923121415590060"><i>“‘I’m an idea.’ He began to devour the ham.”</i><br/><br/>Anyone who has a passing familiarity with literature of the early Twentieth Century will recognize the style, themes, and overall gist of <i>Fog</i>. It plays with its own self-awareness in a way that feels very specifically of-its-era. It’s a pleasure to read insofar as one enjoys relics from another time, but if your eyes tend to roll at yet <i>another</i> story of a man working out his existential issues through confused relationships with women—this one may not </span>
  <span id="freeText17318923121415590060" style="display:none"><i>“‘I’m an idea.’ He began to devour the ham.”</i><br /><br />Anyone who has a passing familiarity with literature of the early Twentieth Century will recognize the style, themes, and overall gist of <i>Fog</i>. It plays with its own self-awareness in a way that feels very specifically of-its-era. It’s a pleasure to read insofar as one enjoys relics from another time, but if your eyes tend to roll at yet <i>another</i> story of a man working out his existential issues through confused relationships with women—this one may not be for you.<br /><br />There is apparently a host of philosophical and theological themes underpinning the narrative, but they’re not particularly burdensome on the reader. Mostly, the tone is mildly satirical and perhaps a little cheeky (not unlike Pirandello, for those familiar with <i>Six Characters in Search of an Author</i>). It's a decent little book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17318923121415590060" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


