              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17215607155958849960">Machado de Assis, Vonnegut&apos;s Brazilian great grandfather, is also father to Unamuno in his &quot;nivola&quot; mode. But it&apos;s Cervantes, in body and spirit, that looms largest here; Unamuno jousts with Quijote to explore the intersection of identity and imagination, in a way that reminds me of Joyce vs Hamlet, only with less contention, more affection. Fun and funny, and Elena Barcia is a pitch-perfect englisher. Here&apos;s to more Unamuno from Northwestern.</span>
  <span id="freeText17215607155958849960" style="display:none">Machado de Assis, Vonnegut's Brazilian great grandfather, is also father to Unamuno in his "nivola" mode. But it's Cervantes, in body and spirit, that looms largest here; Unamuno jousts with Quijote to explore the intersection of identity and imagination, in a way that reminds me of Joyce vs Hamlet, only with less contention, more affection. Fun and funny, and Elena Barcia is a pitch-perfect englisher. Here's to more Unamuno from Northwestern.</span>
