<div id="review_3719344521" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3719344521" />
    <a title="Benoît" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8593248-beno-t"><img alt="Benoît" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1538568913p2/8593248.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3719344521?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Benoît" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Benoît" href="/user/show/8593248-beno-t">Benoît</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3719344521" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6077299228146008531">Surprising modernist novella, full of dialogues and very playful, and a pioneer in its anticipation of existentialism, surrealism and Joyce. Augusto is an orphaned dandy who falls in love on the first page after meeting a pair of eyes in the street that look like twin stars to him. He follows the stars to her house. Everyone is encouraging him to marry, starting with her aunt and uncle, but the beautiful Eugenia sees differently.<br/><br/>Augusto is naive, idealistic and disconnected, but he’s also proud.</span>
  <span id="freeText6077299228146008531" style="display:none">Surprising modernist novella, full of dialogues and very playful, and a pioneer in its anticipation of existentialism, surrealism and Joyce. Augusto is an orphaned dandy who falls in love on the first page after meeting a pair of eyes in the street that look like twin stars to him. He follows the stars to her house. Everyone is encouraging him to marry, starting with her aunt and uncle, but the beautiful Eugenia sees differently.<br /><br />Augusto is naive, idealistic and disconnected, but he’s also proud. Under the pen of Unamuno, he is a Quixotic figure looking for love. Eugenia is an impatient, no-nonsense early feminist. We have another pair of hilarious characters in uncle Don Fermín, a Sternian figure who claims to be a mystic anarchist but only in theory, and his wife who constantly shuts him up. Finally, the main frame story is interspersed with the tales of Augusto’s friends about their own marriages. The structure is overall very loose and free.<br /><br />The tone is hard to pin down, somehow satire verging alternatively on the silly and profound. It seems pointless as a social commentary, Augusto being too disconnected and conservative to deserve much better. But I highly appreciated it in a more artistic sense for the humor, the clashes between what exists only in our head and the circumstances, and how life can play cruel jokes on us.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6077299228146008531" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

