<div id="review_14751517" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/14751517" />
    <a title="Anne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/882395-anne"><img alt="Anne" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/14751517?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne" href="/user/show/882395-anne">Anne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780252068942" href="/book/show/144920.Mist">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer14751517" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15024047080688720755">For fans of early 20th century European modernism, this novel provides the reader a natural step from positivism to vanguardism. Unamuno, clearly well versed in the works of Pirandello and Dario, creates a space where he himself becomes a character and the reader is left to guess who is in charge of the penning of the novel. Unlike any other novel I have read, Unamuno is cognizant of his writing prowess; he labels his work &apos;nivola&apos; because the term novel is too unilateral. Infused with Hegelian </span>
  <span id="freeText15024047080688720755" style="display:none">For fans of early 20th century European modernism, this novel provides the reader a natural step from positivism to vanguardism. Unamuno, clearly well versed in the works of Pirandello and Dario, creates a space where he himself becomes a character and the reader is left to guess who is in charge of the penning of the novel. Unlike any other novel I have read, Unamuno is cognizant of his writing prowess; he labels his work 'nivola' because the term novel is too unilateral. Infused with Hegelian idealism, any philosophy fan as well as the adventurous reader will find this 'nivola' not only a great introduction to Spanish modernism but also worthy of further rumination. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15024047080688720755" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


